## Gauge Style (CRITICAL for Frontend TypeScript App)

**For the modern TypeScript/Next.js frontend**, gauges MUST use the **two-ring SVG circular progress** style (matching the IHPI Score gauges), NOT the old-fashioned speedometer-style ECharts gauges.

### Required Gauge Style
- **Thin circular ring** (strokeWidth 6-8px) as background (light opacity)
- **Colored progress arc** on top using strokeDasharray
- **Large bold number** centered inside the ring
- **Color determined by value**: green (#27ae60) for good, yellow (#f39c12) for caution, red (#e74c3c) for danger
- **Small label text** below the gauge (metric name + unit)
- **No tick marks, no pointer, no split lines, no axis labels**
- Use pure SVG `<circle>` elements, NOT ECharts gauge series

### SVG Ring Gauge Pattern
```tsx
<div className="relative w-24 h-24 mx-auto">
  <svg className="w-full h-full transform -rotate-90">
    <circle cx="48" cy="48" r="40" fill="none"
      stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="8"
      className="text-muted/30" />
    <circle cx="48" cy="48" r="40" fill="none"
      stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="8"
      strokeDasharray={`${(value / max) * 251.2} 251.2`}
      className={colorClass} strokeLinecap="round" />
  </svg>
  <div className="absolute inset-0 flex items-center justify-center">
    <span className="text-2xl font-bold">{value}</span>
  </div>
</div>
```

### When to Use ECharts vs SVG Gauges
- **SVG Ring Gauges**: Dashboard overview cards, small status indicators, ICE station sensors, space weather indices
- **ECharts**: Heatmaps, radar charts, line charts, bar charts, scatter plots — NOT for simple value gauges

